I got covid last sunday. Didn't get the vaccines. Here's how it's gone so far:

- There was chills and mild fever on the first day. It started with a feeling of nausea but I didn't vomit.
- The second day the fever had lowered but I welt tired and a bit achy.
- The third day the fever was gone and I was feeling pretty good, some runny nose and a bit of a cough.
- The fourth day was similar to the the day before but the cough got a bit worse over the evening.
- Now I'm on my fifth day and I feel otherwise fine but there's some chest congestion and there's a need to cough to clear it up. It gets a bit more congested when sleeping.

I have a pulse oximeter and the oxygen levels are great (99-98%) but pulse is a bit high (80-90). I hope the cough/congestion doesn't get too bad. I have a tendency of getting a nasty cough and a need of clearing up the lungs in the morning even with regular viruses, so I dunno if it's a good sign or not. In other hand this feels very typical respitory illness, but you never know if it gets worse.

Quercetin has long been evaluated for its potential protective effects against cancers, heart disease, and cells that release histamines.

Using this rationale, researchers are postulating that vitamin C should be administered with quercetin because it can recycle oxidized quercetin, producing a synergistic effect and enhancing quercetin's antiviralpcapability, Biancatelli added.
After the 2003 SARS-CoV-1 coronavirus outbreak, researchers in China found quercetin and other small molecules bound to the spike protein of the virus, interfering with its ability to infect host cells.

Human Studies
The signal from the SARS-CoV-1 study led researcher Hasan √ñnal, MD, and co-authors to conduct an open-label randomized control trial in Turkey examining quercetin's role in COVID-19. In the trial, 95 patients with COVID-19 are receiving a 1,000-mg active treatment dose and 113 healthcare workers are receiving a 500-mg dose as prophylaxis. In both treatment arms, quercetin is administered with vitamin C and bromelain, a supplement extracted from pineapples that is used for burns or inflammation.

I DID THIS!  Short version: Basically, all on my own, immune deficient, 63 yr old with heart issues, asthma, hx of pneumonia. Could not get tested due to no known positive exposure. So I took zinc (in a throat spray with eucalyptus), Vit C, Vit D, and hyperthermia. After testing positive 6 weeks later, I added NAC, magnesium, melatonin. I also used proning in March when breathing was really difficult:  My grandmother taught me to do that in 1963 when my lungs got congested. 

Was infected March 13, my doctor did not believe it possible for me to have caught it in Maine at the time, and anyway, they had nothing, nothing to offer. So I isolated and used what was on hand: my grandmother's advice to "sweat it out" would be impossible because my body would not mount a fever!  BUT in January, I had purchased a cheap flimsy nylon fabric one-person sauna from China (and then let it sit for a month in case it had virus - hey, we knew nothing about it at the time!) - just in case I got sick. So every other day in March, April, May, I turned on the Maine CDC radio update and took a 35 minute sauna. I was finally tested when a nurse heard my horrible-sounding cough over the phone - and yes, after TOTAL isolation, I still tested positive at 6 weeks post onset of symptoms.  Symptoms lasted until Christmas - and still have lung pain. 

But now I can tell my skeptical friends that, yes, MAYBE my cheap little $50 fabric sauna saved my life - just as I thought it did.

38:52 Re "portable HEPA filter unit."  These can be readily fabricated for $40 and can filter 1500+ cubic feet of air per minute, which is often more than an expensive "HEPA filter."  

No special skill is required to assemble but two items:  a 20-in. box fan, which costs $20,  and a 20-in. MERV-13 furnace filter which costs  about $20.  Simply use masking tape or any other suitable tape to securely affix the filter on the input side of the fan.  Obviously, two or more of these could be used in a room or throughout a home; could also be used in office settings and many other situations of course.  A single fan is thus capable of theoretically filtering all the air in a good-sized bedroom at least once every 60 seconds.  I think this is critical for slowing the spread in at-home Covid settings.

A MERV-13 filter will capture up to 75 percent of particles 0.3 to 1.0 microns in size.  A MERV-16 filter will capture at least 95 percent of such sized particles.  Thus, either is capable of capturing SARS-Cov-2 and other viruses and bacteria, although I believe some SARS Cov-2 virons may be as small as 0.1 microns -??  These filters will also capture lead dust, smoke,  and other toxins.  Note that there are two other rating systems for filters, Home Depot (MPR) and 3M (FPR) have their own, but there are comparison charts online.  

Also, if one has a forced air heating and/or cooling system, more efficient filters should be utilized as well in the furnace or a/c unit as air is circulated throughout the entire living space (note that there will be more air flow resistance with more efficient filters, check maximum efficiency stated by the manufacturer).  More information about filters, fan air flow rates, virus and bacteria sizes, etc. can be gleaned from the internet for those interested.
